The paper deals with deep reinforcement learning applied to open-domain dialog generation, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP). Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves the use of pre-trained models and uncertainty estimates, which are common techniques in machine learning and artificial intelligence, respectively, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) likely sub-categories as well. The paper also discusses the use of human interaction data, which is relevant to the sub-category of cs.SD (Software Engineering). Finally, the paper tests the real-world generalization of the developed algorithms by deploying them live to converse with humans, which falls under the sub-category of cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction).
